85 (12) IN-NETWORK. When an emergency medical service
86 provider is in a contract with a health care insurer to
87 provide covered services in the health care insurer's provider
88 network.
89 (13) OUT-OF-NETWORK. When an emergency medical service
90 provider does not have a contract with a health care insurer
91 to provide covered services in the health care insurer's
92 provider network.
93 (14) TREAT IN PLACE. An emergency response event in
94 which an emergency medical service provider that would
95 otherwise provide the emergency ground transport assesses an
96 enrollee and renders basic life support at his or her location
97 without emergency ground transport.
98 Section 2. (a)(1) A health care insurer shall contract
99 with any willing emergency medical service provider to provide
100 covered services in the health care insurer's provider network
101 under terms extended to comparable providers that are
102 in-network.
103 (2) An in-network provider shall meet licensing
104 requirements provided by law.
105 (b)(1) Beginning October 1, 2026, the minimum
106 reimbursement from a health insurer to an emergency medical
107 service provider that is in-network for emergency ground
108 transport shall be 200 percent of the Medicare Ambulance Fee
109 Schedule rate as published by the Centers for Medicare &
110 Medicaid Services (CMS).
111 (2)a. Beginning January 1, 2027, the minimum
112 reimbursement from a health insurer to an emergency medical
Page 4

reimbursement from a health insurer to an emergency medical
5VX5N66-1 02/25/2026 JC (H) HSE 2026-264
House Ways and Means General Fund Reported
Substitute for HB400
113 service provider that is in-network for treat in place shall
114 be 200 percent of the Medicare Ambulance Fee Schedule rate for
115 basic life support as published by CMS which is in effect on
116 January 1, 2027.
117 b. Submission of a claim for reimbursement for treat in
118 place is prohibited if the emergency medical service provider
119 has submitted a claim for emergency ground transport for the
120 same event or occurrence.
121 (c)(1) Beginning January 1, 2027, the minimum
122 reimbursement amount from a health care insurer to an
123 emergency medical service provider that is out-of-network for
124 covered services shall be 180 percent of the Medicare
125 Ambulance Fee Schedule rate as published by CMS.
126 (2) The minimum reimbursement rate for treat in place
127 provided in paragraph (b)(2)a. shall not apply to an
128 out-of-network emergency medical service provider.
129 (d)(1) For purposes of this section, the Medicare
130 Ambulance Fee Schedule rate shall be the rate applicable to
131 zip code 35462, including the applicable Medicare base rate
132 and mileage components.
133 (2) The reimbursement rate established under this
134 section shall be applied uniformly on a statewide basis,
135 without regard to the geographic locality, population density,
136 or zip code in which the ground ambulance service is
137 furnished.
138 Section 3. (a)(1) Payment in accordance with Section 2
139 shall be payment in full for covered services.
140 (2) An emergency medical service provider, whether
Page 5

(2) An emergency medical service provider, whether
5VX5N66-1 02/25/2026 JC (H) HSE 2026-264
House Ways and Means General Fund Reported
Substitute for HB400
141 in-network or out-of-network, including the provider's agent,
142 contractor, or assignee, may not bill or seek collection of
143 any amount from an enrollee except for the enrollee's
144 in-network cost-sharing amount.
145 (3) The health care insurer shall certify an enrollee's
146 in-network cost-sharing amount to an out-of-network provider
147 upon request.
148 (b)(1) Not later than 30 days after receipt of a clean
149 electronic claim, or not later than 45 days after receipt of a
150 clean written claim, a health care insurer shall remit payment
151 to an out-of-network emergency medical service provider and
152 shall not send payment to an enrollee.
153 (2) If a claim for reimbursement submitted by an
154 emergency medical service provider to a health care insurer is
155 not a clean claim, not later than 30 days after receiving the
156 claim, the health care insurer shall send the provider a
157 written receipt acknowledging the claim, accompanied with one
158 of the following applicable statements:
159 a. The insurer is declining to pay all or a part of the
160 claim, with the specific reason for the denial.
161 b. Additional information is necessary to determine if
162 the claim is payable, with the specific additional information
163 that is required.
164 (3) In no event shall a health care insurer require the
165 provider to submit either of the following as a condition to
166 the acceptance and processing of an initial claim as a clean
167 claim:
168 a. Data elements in excess of those required on the
Page 6

a. Data elements in excess of those required on the
