241 Section 5. (a) The Alabama Association of Ambulance
242 Services shall contract with a business school, accredited by
243 the Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business,
244 located at a doctoral granting regional institution with
245 research college and university Carnegie classification status
246 which has expertise in risk management and insurance, to study
247 the impact of Sections 1 through 4 on the provision of
248 emergency medical services.
249 (b) The consultant shall produce a report on the
250 findings, which shall not exceed fifty thousand dollars
251 ($50,000) in cost, the cost to be borne by the three largest
252 health care insurers as measured by the number of enrollees in
Page 9

health care insurers as measured by the number of enrollees in
5VX5N66-1 02/25/2026 JC (H) HSE 2026-264
House Ways and Means General Fund Reported
Substitute for HB400
253 the state, and which also offer individual health care benefit
254 plans on the Health Insurance Marketplace.
255 (c) In addition to findings on the impact of Sections 1
256 through 4 on the provision of emergency medical services, the
257 report shall include, but not be limited to, the following:
258 (1) Measures taken by other states on the provision of
259 emergency medical services and the effectiveness of those
260 measures.
261 (2) Recommendations of measures that would balance the
262 goals of ensuring adequate access to emergency medical
263 services with the cost burden of such measures on the state,
264 its employers, and residents.
265 (d) The report shall be submitted to the President Pro
266 Tempore of the Senate and the Speaker of the House of
267 Representatives no later than December 1, 2028.
268 Section 6. Sections 1 through 5 are repealed on June 1,
269 2029.
